<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41202328</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>06</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>06</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1364-6915</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>30</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Aging &amp; mental health</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Aging Ment Health</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Flywheel resistance training and depressive symptoms in older women: a randomized controlled trial.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>573</StartPage><EndPage>586</EndPage><MedlinePgn>573-586</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1080/13607863.2025.2575025</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVES" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">This randomized controlled trial compared flywheel-based resistance training with traditional resistance training on depressive symptoms in sedentary older women.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHOD" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Twenty-nine women aged &#x2265;60 years without clinical depression were randomized (blocks of 2 and 4) to flywheel (<i>n</i> = 14) or traditional resistance training (<i>n</i> = 15) for 8 weeks (six exercises, twice weekly) at the Federal University of Vi&#xe7;osa, Brazil. Flywheel devices provide inertial resistance and eccentric overload by storing and releasing kinetic energy. Depressive symptoms were the primary outcome. Allocation was concealed with sealed envelopes; outcome assessors and the principal investigator were blinded.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Twenty-eight participants completed the protocol; one dropout in the traditional group required multiple imputation. Adjusted depressive symptom scores were 2.7 &#xb1; 2.7 in the flywheel group (&#x2193;2.5 points) and 2.0 &#xb1; 2.8 in the traditional group (&#x2193;2.0 points), with no between-group difference (p = 0.193). The effect size was small (&#x3b7;p&#xb2; = 0.03) and statistical power was low (1-&#x3b2; = 0.25). All adverse events were mild (grade 1); no serious events occurred.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Both flywheel and traditional resistance training showed potential to reduce depressive symptoms in sedentary older women. Larger trials are warranted.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="TRIAL REGISTRATION" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">ClinicalTrials.gov NCT05910632.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Andr&#xe9;s P&#xe9;rez Bedoya</LastName><ForeName>&#xc9;dison</ForeName><Initials>&#xc9;</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-1929-9132</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Bachelor of Physical Education, Recreation and Sports, Faculty of Education and Social Sciences, Antioquia Institute of Technology-University Institution, Medell&#xed;n, Colombia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Human Morphophysiology Analysis Laboratory (HUMANLAB), Federal University of Vi&#xe7;osa, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Puerta-L&#xf3;pez</LastName><ForeName>Luisa Fernanda</ForeName><Initials>LF</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-6177-1456</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Research group on physical activity for health (AFIS), Antioquia University, Medell&#xed;n, Colombia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Garcia Agostinho</LastName><ForeName>Pablo Augusto</ForeName><Initials>PA</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-4939-136X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Human Morphophysiology Analysis Laboratory (HUMANLAB), Federal University of Vi&#xe7;osa, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><A